					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/littlesallydigby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1910986); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1910986&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610164649" alt="LittleSallyDigby" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1910986)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/littlesallydigby" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1910986); return false;" >LittleSallyDigby</a></span> <span class="odate time_1457006515 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">03 Mar 2016 12:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2466881">
									

<p>The thing that makes this act stand out from the others, for me, is the lack of a book page combined with the &quot;one day only&quot; note. Where did this guy really come from? How did he come to Fuller's? Why was he only there once? (Why did the circus <em>know</em> he was only going to be there once?) What happened to him afterward? We just don't know, and that opens up all sorts of space for headcanons and/or further development of the Fuller's concept.</p>

							</div>

								
					
